version: 1
display_name: VCFE-9X-000213 - The ESX host Secure Shell (SSH) daemon must ignore .rhosts files.
global_description: |-
  SSH trust relationships mean a compromise on one host can allow an attacker to move trivially to other hosts. SSH can emulate the behavior of the obsolete "rsh" command in allowing users to enable insecure access to their accounts via ".rhosts" files.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFE-9X-000213
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000480-VMM-002000
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_esx:
    type: custom
    desc: The ESX host Secure Shell (SSH) daemon must ignore .rhosts files.
    control_id: VCFE-9X-000213
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From an ESX shell, run the following command:

      # esxcli system ssh server config list -k ignorerhosts

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following commands:

      $esxcli = Get-EsxCli -v2
      $esxcli.system.ssh.server.config.list.invoke() | Where-Object {$_.Key -eq 'ignorerhosts'}

      Example result:

      ignorerhosts yes

      If "ignorerhosts" is not configured to "yes", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      SSH trust relationships mean a compromise on one host can allow an attacker to move trivially to other hosts. SSH can emulate the behavior of the obsolete "rsh" command in allowing users to enable insecure access to their accounts via ".rhosts" files.
    remediation: |-
      From an ESX shell, run the following command:

      # esxcli system ssh server config set -k ignorerhosts -v yes

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following commands:

      $esxcli = Get-EsxCli -v2
      $arguments = $esxcli.system.ssh.server.config.set.CreateArgs()
      $arguments.keyword = 'ignorerhosts'
      $arguments.value = 'yes'
      $esxcli.system.ssh.server.config.set.Invoke($arguments)
